performance_optimizations.description:
Q3 currently sorts ~300K aggregated groups by revenue DESC to get top 10. This is O(n log n) = 300K * log(300K) ≈ 5.5M comparisons. For top-k queries, partial_sort or priority queue reduces to O(n log k) where k=10.

**Implementation in queries/q3.cpp:**
Replace:
```cpp
std::sort(results.begin(), results.end(), comparator);
if (results.size() > 10) results.resize(10);
```
With:
```cpp
if (results.size() > 10) {
    std::partial_sort(results.begin(), results.begin() + 10, results.end(), comparator);
    results.resize(10);
} else {
    std::sort(results.begin(), results.end(), comparator);
}
```

**Expected impact:** Sorting time reduction from O(n log n) to O(n log k). For n=300K, k=10: theoretical 100x speedup in sort phase. Estimated overall Q3 time: 1272ms → 1200ms (5% improvement, as sort is <10% of total time).

**Risk:** Very low - std::partial_sort is standard library, well-tested.

Q3's parallel scans copy entire columns into thread-local vectors, then merge them. For lineitem (60M rows), this means:
- Thread-local: 64 threads × (60M/64 ≈ 937K rows) × (8 bytes orderkey + 8 bytes index) = 960MB of temporary allocations
- Merge: Copy 960MB again into final vector
Total: 1.9GB of data movement for a table that's already in memory via mmap.

**Root cause:** The code builds orderkeys and indices vectors per thread, then merges them before probing the hash join.

**Solution - Direct Hash Probe Without Intermediate Copies:**
Instead of:
1. Parallel scan → thread-local vectors
2. Merge vectors
3. Probe hash join with merged vectors

Do:
1. Parallel scan → directly probe hash join → thread-local match vectors
2. Merge match results only (much smaller - only matching rows)

**Implementation sketch in queries/q3.cpp:**
```cpp
// Instead of building lineitem_orderkeys + lineitem_indices per thread, then merging:
std::vector<std::vector<JoinMatch>> thread_matches(num_threads);

for (size_t t = 0; t < num_threads; ++t) {
    threads.emplace_back([&, t]() {
        size_t start_idx = t * chunk_size;
        size_t end_idx = std::min(start_idx + chunk_size, lineitem.size());

        auto& local_matches = thread_matches[t];
        for (size_t i = start_idx; i < end_idx; ++i) {
            if (lineitem.l_shipdate[i] > ship_cutoff) {  // Filter
                auto* match = lineitem_join.probe_key(lineitem.l_orderkey[i]);
                if (match) {
                    local_matches.push_back({i, *match});
                }
            }
        }
    });
}
// Merge: Only copy matching rows (selectivity ~2% = 1.2M rows), not entire table (60M)
```

**Expected impact:** Eliminate 1.9GB of data copies. On a system with ~30GB/s memory bandwidth, this saves 1900MB/30000MB/s ≈ 63ms. Similar savings for customer and orders scans. Total estimated: 1272ms → 1100ms (13% improvement).

Q6 evaluates 4 predicates on every row:
1. l_shipdate >= date_start (int32 comparison)
2. l_shipdate < date_end (int32 comparison)
3. l_discount >= 0.05 && l_discount <= 0.07 (double comparison)
4. l_quantity < 24 (double comparison)

With AVX2, we can evaluate 8 int32 comparisons or 4 double comparisons per instruction. The CPU supports avx2 (confirmed via lscpu).

**Implementation in queries/q6.cpp or operators/scan.h:**
```cpp
#include <immintrin.h>

// SIMD-vectorized predicate for Q6
size_t q6_filter_simd(const LineitemTable& table, size_t start, size_t end, 
                      int32_t date_start, int32_t date_end, 
                      double disc_min, double disc_max, double qty_max,
                      std::vector<size_t>& matches) {
    __m256i date_start_vec = _mm256_set1_epi32(date_start);
    __m256i date_end_vec = _mm256_set1_epi32(date_end);
    __m256d disc_min_vec = _mm256_set1_pd(disc_min);
    __m256d disc_max_vec = _mm256_set1_pd(disc_max);
    __m256d qty_max_vec = _mm256_set1_pd(qty_max);

    size_t i = start;
    // Process 8 rows at a time (AVX2 width for int32)
    for (; i + 8 <= end; i += 8) {
        // Load and compare dates (8 at once)
        __m256i dates = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)&table.l_shipdate[i]);
        __m256i date_ge = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(dates, date_start_vec);  // >= start
        __m256i date_lt = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(date_end_vec, dates);    // < end
        __m256i date_mask = _mm256_and_si256(date_ge, date_lt);

        // For matching dates, check discount/quantity (4 doubles at a time)
        int date_bits = _mm256_movemask_epi8(date_mask);
        if (date_bits != 0) {
            // Check each of 8 positions (simplified - full impl would batch this)
            for (int j = 0; j < 8; ++j) {
                if ((date_bits >> (j*4)) & 0xF) {
                    if (table.l_discount[i+j] >= disc_min && 
                        table.l_discount[i+j] <= disc_max &&
                        table.l_quantity[i+j] < qty_max) {
                        matches.push_back(i+j);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    // Scalar tail for remaining rows
    for (; i < end; ++i) {
        if (table.l_shipdate[i] >= date_start && table.l_shipdate[i] < date_end &&
            table.l_discount[i] >= disc_min && table.l_discount[i] <= disc_max &&
            table.l_quantity[i] < qty_max) {
            matches.push_back(i);
        }
    }
    return matches.size();
}
```

**Integration:** Replace the predicate lambda in parallel_scan_aggregate with SIMD version.

**Expected impact:** Date comparisons: 8x speedup (8 comparisons per instruction). Overall filter: 2-3x speedup. Q6 is currently 44ms, with ~50% time in filter → 44ms → 30ms.

Q1 filters l_shipdate <= cutoff_date for 60M rows. Currently scalar comparison. With AVX2, evaluate 8 date comparisons per instruction.

**Implementation in queries/q1.cpp:**
Modify the aggregation function to use SIMD for the date filter:
```cpp
auto agg_func = [&lineitem, cutoff_date](Q1AggTable& table, size_t start, size_t end) {
    __m256i cutoff_vec = _mm256_set1_epi32(cutoff_date);

    for (size_t i = start; i + 8 <= end; i += 8) {
        __m256i dates = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)&lineitem.l_shipdate[i]);
        __m256i cmp = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(cutoff_vec, dates);  // dates <= cutoff
        int mask = _mm256_movemask_epi8(cmp);

        // Process matching rows (98% of rows match, so most will pass)
        for (int j = 0; j < 8; ++j) {
            if ((mask >> (j*4)) & 0xF) {
                CompositeKey key{lineitem.l_returnflag[i+j], lineitem.l_linestatus[i+j]};
                auto& state = table[key];
                // ... aggregation logic
            }
        }
    }
    // Scalar tail
};
```

**Note:** Since 98% of rows pass the filter (low selectivity), SIMD benefit is modest. Main gain is evaluating 8 dates per instruction before checking aggregation.

**Expected impact:** 5-10% speedup in scan phase. Q1 total: 378ms → 350ms.
